{"title_page": "Ain Sifni", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Ain Sifni\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =\n|settlement_type        = \n|image_skyline          = File:Ainsifni.png\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Iraq\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Region\n|subdivision_name1      ={{flag|Kurdistan Region}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Governorates of Iraq|Governorate]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Nineveh Governorate]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Iraq|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Shekhan District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      =\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|population_as_of               = 2014\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_total               =16,000<ref name=\"csm\" />\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone=\n|utc_offset=\n|timezone_DST=\n|utc_offset_DST=\n|coordinates            ={{coord|36|41|30|N|43|21|00|E}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Ain Sifni''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u064a\u0646 \u0633\u0641\u0646\u064a}},{{refn|Alternatively transliterated as \u02bfAyn Sifni,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://syriaca.org/place/941.html|title=\u02bfAyn Sifni|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=The Syriac Gazetteer|access-date=11 April 2020}} </ref> Ainsefni,<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" /> or Ean Sefne.<ref name=\"Eansefne\"/>|group=nb}}<ref name=\"wg\">{{cite web |url=https://archive.is/20130209114015/http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php#selection-145.0-145.8|title='Ayn Sifn\u012b|author=<!--Not stated--> |website=World Gazetteer|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> {{lang-ku|\u0634\u06ce\u062e\u0627\u0646\u200e|\u015e\u00eaxan}}){{refn|Alternatively transliterated as Sheikhan,<ref name=\"csm\">{{cite news |title=A sanctuary for Iraqi Yazidis \u2013 and a plea for Obama's intervention|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2014/0812/A-sanctuary-for-Iraqi-Yazidis-and-a-plea-for-Obama-s-intervention|last1=Soguel|first1=Dominique|date=12 August 2014|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]}}</ref> Shekhan.<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" />|group=nb}}<ref name=\"\u015e\u00caXAN\">{{cite news |title=\u015e\u00caXAN - Li kampa Kurd\u00ean \u00cazid\u00ee leh\u00ee rab\u00fb \u00fb av\u00ea da bin 30 \u00e7adiran |url=https://www.rudaw.net/kurmanci/kurdistan/231120187 |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=[[Rudaw Media Network]]|date=23 November 2018 |language=ku}}</ref> is a town and district in [[Nineveh Governorate]] in [[Kurdistan Region]], [[Iraq]]. It is located in the [[Nineveh Plains]].\n\nIn the town, there is a [[Chaldean Catholic Church|Chaldean Catholic]] church of Mar Yousif, and a church of Mar Gewargis of the [[Ancient Church of the East]].<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" /><ref name=\"Eansefne\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35628.html|title=Mar Yousif church \u2013 Eansefne|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 November 2011|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35598.html|title=Mar Gewragiz church \u2013 Ean Sefne|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=29 October 2011|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> There is also a [[Yazidism|Yazidi]] shrine of [[Sheikh Adi ibn Musafir|Sheikh Adi]].<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,36340.html|title=Shekhan (Ainsefni)|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 December 2012|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe Kurdish name of the town is derived from the plural form of \"[[sheikh]]\" (\"holy man\" in Kurdish), and thus translates to \"[the land of the] holy men\".<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" /><ref name=\"csm\" />\n\n==History==\nAin Sifni may have originally been a Christian village, but likely converted in the 13th/14th centuries, and a Yazidi community was present by the 19th century.<ref>Wilmshurst (2000), p. 203</ref> The district was founded on 16 December 1924.<ref name=\"capi\">{{cite web|title=Basic information about Shekhan District|url=http://www.capiraq.org/Maps/Data3/Shekhan.pdf|website=Christian Aid Programme in Iraq |accessdate=October 7, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425080258/http://www.capiraq.org/Maps/Data3/Shekhan.pdf|archivedate=April 25, 2012|format=PDF}}</ref> The Chaldean church of Mar Yousif was rebuilt in 1960, replacing an older church built in 1946-1948.<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" />\n\nDuring the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], two Iraqi military installations near Ain Sifni were struck by [[United States of America|US]] airstrikes on 24 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bombing raids signal start of mountain offensive|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/mar/25/iraq.lukeharding|last1=Harding|first1=Luke|last2=Howard|first2=Michael |date=25 March 2003|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Two battalions of the Iraqi 108th Regiment, 8th Infantry Division, were stationed at the town at this time.<ref name=\"Finlayson75\">Finlayson (2005), p. 75</ref> The US bombing campaign against the garrison was ineffective, and an entire Iraqi battalion withdrew with no casualties.<ref name=\"Finlayson75\" /> On 6 April, [[United States Army Special Forces#Basic Element \u2013 SF Operational Detachment-A (SFODA) composition|ODAs]] 051, 055, and 056 of the US [[10th Special Forces Group (United States)|10th Special Forces Group]] and 300 [[Peshmerga]] soldiers of the 12th ''Supay'' (battalion) seized the town, and 33 Iraqis were killed, 54 wounded, and 230 taken prisoner, and 1 Peshmerga casualty.<ref>Finlayson (2005), p. 78</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]] (KRG) signed a [[Production sharing agreement|production sharing contract]] with [[Hunt Oil Company]] to extract oil near Ain Sifni, despite the town being officially outside the control of the KRG, and has since been declared illegal by the Iraqi government.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Ben|last1=Lando|title=Hunt Oil knew KRG oil deal in disputed territory|url=https://www.iraqoilreport.com/news/hunt-oil-knew-krg-oil-deal-in-disputed-territory-6108/|date=25 August 2011|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=Iraq Oil Report}}</ref> The concession at Ain Sifni is estimated to have reservoirs of 900 million recoverable barrels of oil.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Christopher |last1=Helman|title=Newest Iraqi Gusher Could Make Texas Oilman A Billionaire|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/christopherhelman/2012/09/13/whos-the-texas-oilman-behind-the-newest-iraqi-gusher/#2d78b2945d6f|date=13 September 2012|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2012, the [[Sarkis Aghajan Mamendo#Activities|Supreme Committee of Christian Affairs]] had constructed a priest house and community hall for local Christians.<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" /> The town had an estimated population of 11,498 in 2013.<ref name=\"wg\" /> Most of the town's population of 16,000 people fled during the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] [[Northern Iraq offensive (August 2014)|offensive]] in August 2014, and under 500 men remained to defend Ain Sifni under the leadership of mayor Mamo al-Bagsri.<ref name=\"csm\" /> Humanitarian aid was delivered to Ain Sifni by the [[Assyrian Aid Society]] in November 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assyrianaidiraq.org/news/943|title=Within The Activities Of AAS-Iraq In Providing Aid To The Displaced Families From Mosul & Nineveh Plain|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=4 November 2014|website=Assyrian Aid Society|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, the refugee camp at Ain Sifni, which is inhabited by Yazidi refugees, was flooded by heavy rainfall.<ref name=\"\u015e\u00caXAN\" /> The town was the residence of the Yazidi Emir [[Tahseen Said]] until he went into exile in [[Germany]], where he died, and was buried at Ain Sifni on 5 February 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince of IS-ravaged Yazidis buried in Iraq|url=https://en.qantara.de/content/prince-of-is-ravaged-yazidis-buried-in-iraq|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[Qantara.de]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/alarabiya-studies/2014/08/11/What-you-did-not-know-about-Iraq-s-Yazidi-minority-.html|title=What you did not know about Iraq\u2019s Yazidi minority |date=11 August 2014|website=[[Al Arabiya]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Ain Sifni is largely populated by Yazidis,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sheikhan: Where Kurdish men go for a second wife|last1=El\u00ee|first1=Nasir|url=https://www.rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/130320191|date=13 March 2019|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[Rudaw Media Network]]}}</ref> most of whom speak [[Kurmanji]] Kurdish.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iraqi Yazidis: 'If we move they will kill us'|last1=Salih |first1=Mohammed A |last2=Wilgenburg|first2=Wladimir van |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/08/iraqi-yazidis-if-move-they-will-kill-us-20148513656188206.html|date=5 August 2014|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n===Climate===\nAin Sifni has a [[mediterranean climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]: ''Csa'').\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Ain Sifni\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n\n|Jan high C = 10.8\t\t\n|Feb high C = 12.7\n|Mar high C = 16.6\n|Apr high C = 22.3\n|May high C = 29.8\n|Jun high C = 36.7\n|Jul high C = 40.9\n|Aug high C = 40.7\n|Sep high C = 36.4\n|Oct high C = 28.7\n|Nov high C = 19.8\n|Dec high C = 12.7\n\n|Jan mean C =  5.9\t\t\n|Feb mean C =  7.5\n|Mar mean C = 10.9\n|Apr mean C = 15.9\n|May mean C = 22.3\n|Jun mean C = 28.0\n|Jul mean C = 32.1\n|Aug mean C = 31.6\n|Sep mean C = 27.2\n|Oct mean C = 20.5\n|Nov mean C = 13.6\n|Dec mean C =  7.7\n\n|Jan low C =  1.0\t\t\n|Feb low C =  2.3\n|Mar low C =  5.3\n|Apr low C =  9.6\n|May low C = 14.9\n|Jun low C = 19.4\n|Jul low C = 22.3\n|Aug low C = 22.5\n|Sep low C = 18.0\n|Oct low C = 12.4\n|Nov low C =  7.5\n|Dec low C =  2.7\n\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 126\t\t\t\t\n|Feb precipitation mm = 149\n|Mar precipitation mm = 138\n|Apr precipitation mm =  97\n|May precipitation mm =  35\n|Jun precipitation mm =   0\n|Jul precipitation mm =   0\n|Aug precipitation mm =   0\n|Sep precipitation mm =   1\n|Oct precipitation mm =  18\n|Nov precipitation mm =  74\n|Dec precipitation mm = 110\n\n|source = https://en.climate-data.org/location/934732/\n|date = 18 January 2018}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Yezidi cemetery in Shexan 6.jpg|Yazidi cemetery in Ain Sifni\nFile:Views around the Ezidi shrine of Nishingaha Peroz (\u0645\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0646\u06cc\u0634\u0646\u06af\u0647\u200c\u0647\u0627 \u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0632) near Shekhan 23.jpg|thumb|Yazidi shrine of Nishingaha Peroz near Ain Sifni\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal|first1=Kenneth |last1= Finlayson|title=This is What You Signed Up For: The Attack on Ayn Sifni|date=2005|journal=Veritas|volume=1|issue=1|pages=75-78|url=https://arsof-history.org/articles/pdf/v1n1_attack_on_ayn_sifni.pdf}}\n* {{cite book | last1 =Wilmshurst| first1 =David|date=2000|title=The Ecclesiastical Organisation of the Church of the East, 1318\u20131913|publisher=Peeters Publishers}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Nineveh Governorate]]\n[[Category:Yazidi populated places in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Ain Sifni\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =\n|settlement_type        = \n|image_skyline          = File:Ainsifni.png\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Iraq\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Region\n|subdivision_name1      ={{flag|Kurdistan Region}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Governorates of Iraq|Governorate]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Nineveh Governorate]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Iraq|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Shekhan District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      =\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|population_as_of               = 2014\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_total               =16,000<ref name=\"csm\" />\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone=\n|utc_offset=\n|timezone_DST=\n|utc_offset_DST=\n|coordinates            ={{coord|36|41|30|N|43|21|00|E}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Ain Sifni'''{{refn|Alternatively transliterated as \u02bfAyn Sifni,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://syriaca.org/place/941.html|title=\u02bfAyn Sifni|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=The Syriac Gazetteer|access-date=11 April 2020}} </ref> Ainsefni,<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" /> or Ean Sefne.<ref name=\"Eansefne\"/>|group=nb}} ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u064a\u0646 \u0633\u0641\u0646\u064a}},<ref name=\"wg\">{{cite web |url=https://archive.is/20130209114015/http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php#selection-145.0-145.8|title='Ayn Sifn\u012b|author=<!--Not stated--> |website=World Gazetteer|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> {{lang-ku|\u0634\u06ce\u062e\u0627\u0646\u200e|\u015e\u00eaxan}}){{refn|Alternatively transliterated as Sheikhan,<ref name=\"csm\">{{cite news |title=A sanctuary for Iraqi Yazidis \u2013 and a plea for Obama's intervention|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2014/0812/A-sanctuary-for-Iraqi-Yazidis-and-a-plea-for-Obama-s-intervention|last1=Soguel|first1=Dominique|date=12 August 2014|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]}}</ref> Shekhan.<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" />|group=nb}}<ref name=\"\u015e\u00caXAN\">{{cite news |title=\u015e\u00caXAN - Li kampa Kurd\u00ean \u00cazid\u00ee leh\u00ee rab\u00fb \u00fb av\u00ea da bin 30 \u00e7adiran |url=https://www.rudaw.net/kurmanci/kurdistan/231120187 |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=[[Rudaw Media Network]]|date=23 November 2018 |language=ku}}</ref> is a town and district in [[Nineveh Governorate]] in [[Kurdistan Region]], [[Iraq]]. It is located in the [[Nineveh Plains]].\n\nIn the town, there is a [[Chaldean Catholic Church|Chaldean Catholic]] church of Mar Yousif, and a church of Mar Gewargis of the [[Ancient Church of the East]].<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" /><ref name=\"Eansefne\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35628.html|title=Mar Yousif church \u2013 Eansefne|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 November 2011|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35598.html|title=Mar Gewragiz church \u2013 Ean Sefne|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=29 October 2011|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> There is also a [[Yazidism|Yazidi]] shrine of [[Sheikh Adi ibn Musafir|Sheikh Adi]].<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,36340.html|title=Shekhan (Ainsefni)|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 December 2012|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe Kurdish name of the town is derived from the plural form of \"[[sheikh]]\" (\"holy man\" in Kurdish), and thus translates to \"[the land of the] holy men\".<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" /><ref name=\"csm\" />\n\n==History==\nAin Sifni may have originally been a Christian village, but likely converted in the 13th/14th centuries, and a Yazidi community was present by the 19th century.<ref>Wilmshurst (2000), p. 203</ref> The district was founded on 16 December 1924.<ref name=\"capi\">{{cite web|title=Basic information about Shekhan District|url=http://www.capiraq.org/Maps/Data3/Shekhan.pdf|website=Christian Aid Programme in Iraq |accessdate=October 7, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425080258/http://www.capiraq.org/Maps/Data3/Shekhan.pdf|archivedate=April 25, 2012|format=PDF}}</ref> The Chaldean church of Mar Yousif was rebuilt in 1960, replacing an older church built in 1946-1948.<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" />\n\nDuring the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], two Iraqi military installations near Ain Sifni were struck by [[United States of America|US]] airstrikes on 24 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bombing raids signal start of mountain offensive|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/mar/25/iraq.lukeharding|last1=Harding|first1=Luke|last2=Howard|first2=Michael |date=25 March 2003|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Two battalions of the Iraqi 108th Regiment, 8th Infantry Division, were stationed at the town at this time.<ref name=\"Finlayson75\">Finlayson (2005), p. 75</ref> The US bombing campaign against the garrison was ineffective, and an entire Iraqi battalion withdrew with no casualties.<ref name=\"Finlayson75\" /> On 6 April, [[United States Army Special Forces#Basic Element \u2013 SF Operational Detachment-A (SFODA) composition|ODAs]] 051, 055, and 056 of the US [[10th Special Forces Group (United States)|10th Special Forces Group]] and 300 [[Peshmerga]] soldiers of the 12th ''Supay'' (battalion) seized the town, and 33 Iraqis were killed, 54 wounded, and 230 taken prisoner, and 1 Peshmerga casualty.<ref>Finlayson (2005), p. 78</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]] (KRG) signed a [[Production sharing agreement|production sharing contract]] with [[Hunt Oil Company]] to extract oil near Ain Sifni, despite the town being officially outside the control of the KRG, and has since been declared illegal by the Iraqi government.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Ben|last1=Lando|title=Hunt Oil knew KRG oil deal in disputed territory|url=https://www.iraqoilreport.com/news/hunt-oil-knew-krg-oil-deal-in-disputed-territory-6108/|date=25 August 2011|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=Iraq Oil Report}}</ref> The concession at Ain Sifni is estimated to have reservoirs of 900 million recoverable barrels of oil.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Christopher |last1=Helman|title=Newest Iraqi Gusher Could Make Texas Oilman A Billionaire|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/christopherhelman/2012/09/13/whos-the-texas-oilman-behind-the-newest-iraqi-gusher/#2d78b2945d6f|date=13 September 2012|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2012, the [[Sarkis Aghajan Mamendo#Activities|Supreme Committee of Christian Affairs]] had constructed a priest house and community hall for local Christians.<ref name=\"Shekhan (Ainsefni)\" /> The town had an estimated population of 11,498 in 2013.<ref name=\"wg\" /> Most of the town's population of 16,000 people fled during the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] [[Northern Iraq offensive (August 2014)|offensive]] in August 2014, and under 500 men remained to defend Ain Sifni under the leadership of mayor Mamo al-Bagsri.<ref name=\"csm\" /> Humanitarian aid was delivered to Ain Sifni by the [[Assyrian Aid Society]] in November 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assyrianaidiraq.org/news/943|title=Within The Activities Of AAS-Iraq In Providing Aid To The Displaced Families From Mosul & Nineveh Plain|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=4 November 2014|website=Assyrian Aid Society|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, the refugee camp at Ain Sifni, which is inhabited by Yazidi refugees, was flooded by heavy rainfall.<ref name=\"\u015e\u00caXAN\" /> The town was the residence of the Yazidi Emir [[Tahseen Said]] until he went into exile in [[Germany]], where he died, and was buried at Ain Sifni on 5 February 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince of IS-ravaged Yazidis buried in Iraq|url=https://en.qantara.de/content/prince-of-is-ravaged-yazidis-buried-in-iraq|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[Qantara.de]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/perspective/alarabiya-studies/2014/08/11/What-you-did-not-know-about-Iraq-s-Yazidi-minority-.html|title=What you did not know about Iraq\u2019s Yazidi minority |date=11 August 2014|website=[[Al Arabiya]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Ain Sifni is largely populated by Yazidis,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sheikhan: Where Kurdish men go for a second wife|last1=El\u00ee|first1=Nasir|url=https://www.rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/130320191|date=13 March 2019|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[Rudaw Media Network]]}}</ref> most of whom speak [[Kurmanji]] Kurdish.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iraqi Yazidis: 'If we move they will kill us'|last1=Salih |first1=Mohammed A |last2=Wilgenburg|first2=Wladimir van |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/08/iraqi-yazidis-if-move-they-will-kill-us-20148513656188206.html|date=5 August 2014|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n===Climate===\nAin Sifni has a [[mediterranean climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]: ''Csa'').\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Ain Sifni\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n\n|Jan high C = 10.8\t\t\n|Feb high C = 12.7\n|Mar high C = 16.6\n|Apr high C = 22.3\n|May high C = 29.8\n|Jun high C = 36.7\n|Jul high C = 40.9\n|Aug high C = 40.7\n|Sep high C = 36.4\n|Oct high C = 28.7\n|Nov high C = 19.8\n|Dec high C = 12.7\n\n|Jan mean C =  5.9\t\t\n|Feb mean C =  7.5\n|Mar mean C = 10.9\n|Apr mean C = 15.9\n|May mean C = 22.3\n|Jun mean C = 28.0\n|Jul mean C = 32.1\n|Aug mean C = 31.6\n|Sep mean C = 27.2\n|Oct mean C = 20.5\n|Nov mean C = 13.6\n|Dec mean C =  7.7\n\n|Jan low C =  1.0\t\t\n|Feb low C =  2.3\n|Mar low C =  5.3\n|Apr low C =  9.6\n|May low C = 14.9\n|Jun low C = 19.4\n|Jul low C = 22.3\n|Aug low C = 22.5\n|Sep low C = 18.0\n|Oct low C = 12.4\n|Nov low C =  7.5\n|Dec low C =  2.7\n\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 126\t\t\t\t\n|Feb precipitation mm = 149\n|Mar precipitation mm = 138\n|Apr precipitation mm =  97\n|May precipitation mm =  35\n|Jun precipitation mm =   0\n|Jul precipitation mm =   0\n|Aug precipitation mm =   0\n|Sep precipitation mm =   1\n|Oct precipitation mm =  18\n|Nov precipitation mm =  74\n|Dec precipitation mm = 110\n\n|source = https://en.climate-data.org/location/934732/\n|date = 18 January 2018}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Yezidi cemetery in Shexan 6.jpg|Yazidi cemetery in Ain Sifni\nFile:Views around the Ezidi shrine of Nishingaha Peroz (\u0645\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0646\u06cc\u0634\u0646\u06af\u0647\u200c\u0647\u0627 \u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0632) near Shekhan 23.jpg|thumb|Yazidi shrine of Nishingaha Peroz near Ain Sifni\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal|first1=Kenneth |last1= Finlayson|title=This is What You Signed Up For: The Attack on Ayn Sifni|date=2005|journal=Veritas|volume=1|issue=1|pages=75-78|url=https://arsof-history.org/articles/pdf/v1n1_attack_on_ayn_sifni.pdf}}\n* {{cite book | last1 =Wilmshurst| first1 =David|date=2000|title=The Ecclesiastical Organisation of the Church of the East, 1318\u20131913|publisher=Peeters Publishers}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Nineveh Governorate]]\n[[Category:Yazidi populated places in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n", "name_user": "Mugsalot", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected layout", "url_page": "