{"title_page": "Nese Malifa", "text_new": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n| image = Valenese Malifa Churchill Cup 2010 vs Russia.jpg\n| birth_name = Valenese Malifa\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|9|10}}\n| birth_place =[[American Samoa]]\n| height = {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|180|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| occupation =\n| school =\n| university = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = [[Ata Malifa]] (twin brother)\n| ru_position = [[Rugby union positions#10. Fly-half|Fly-half]]\n| ru_amateuryears = 2009<br>2010-2015\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Belmont Shore RFC]]<br>[[Glendale Merlins|Glendale Raptors]]\n| ru_clubyears = 2019-present\n| ru_proclubs = [[Rugby ATL]]\n| ru_clubcaps = \n| ru_clubpoints = \n| ru_nationalyears = 2007\u20132011\n| ru_nationalteam = [[United States national rugby union team|United States]]\n| ru_nationalcaps = 24\n| ru_nationalpoints = (63)\n| ru_sevensnationalyears = 2007-\n| ru_sevensnationalteam  = [[United States national rugby sevens team|United States]]\n| ru_sevensnationalcomp  = 17   (307)\n| website = \n}}\n'''Valenese Malifa''' (born 10 September 1985 in [[American Samoa]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[rugby union]] [[Rugby union positions#10. Fly-half|fly-half]]. He was a member of the [[United States national rugby union team]] from 2007 until 2011, and participated with the squad at the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>[http://www.scrum.com/scrum/rugby/player/15532.html Player Profile]</ref>\n\n==Youth==\nNese Malifa played rugby since he was 17 years old. He played for Auckland and Samoa Rugby Clubs. During his stint in the Pacific Islands, Malifa was a representative rugby player in Auckland in both the XV\u2019s and Sevens game, as well as playing representative rugby in Samoa. Malifa\u2019s talents were noticed by selectors while playing for Ponsonby and then the Eden Club in Auckland. Lesser known are Malifa\u2019s talents in other sporting codes, as Malifa represented Samoa in Cricket.\n\n==Career==\nMalifa played club rugby since moving to the U.S. mainland in 2006, first with [[Belmont Shore]], who Malifa helped reach the 2006 national championship.<ref>Glendale Raptors, [http://www.glendalerugby.com/schedule/2011-2012-season/item/1956-nese-malifa\u2019s-rugby-fairy-tale Nese Malifa's rugby fairy tale], Dec. 5, 2011</ref> Malifa moved to Denver in 2010, where he has been playing with the Glendale Raptors.<ref>Glendale Raptors, [http://www.glendalerugby.com/schedule/2011-2012-season/item/1956-nese-malifa\u2019s-rugby-fairy-tale Nese Malifa's rugby fairy tale], Dec. 5, 2011</ref>\n\nMalifa played flyhalf for the USA Hawks match against Canada West in the 2007 [[North America 4]], notching all of his team's points through two converted tries and two penalty goals from two attempts.\n\nMalifa played flyhalf for the [[United States national rugby union team|United States national team]] since his debut against the England Saxons in 2007.  Malifa made two appearances at the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]] in France, and played 3 matches for the U.S. at the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] in New Zealand. Malifa's highest scoring match to date was against Russia in the [[2011 Churchill Cup]], where Malifa kicked 2 penalties and 3 conversions to lead the team in scoring with 12 points, as the U.S. edged out Russia 32-25.<ref>ESPN Scrum, [http://www.espnscrum.com/churchill-cup-2011/rugby/story/141817.html USA beat Russia for Bowl title], June 18, 2011</ref> As of December 2011, Malifa has tallied 24 caps and 63 points for the U.S. national team.<ref>USA Rugby, [http://web.usarugby.org/cgi-bin/viadesto/natteams/mnt/15ProfileDetail.pl?playerId=367 Men's National Team, Player Profile]</ref>\n\nMalifa plays flyhalf for the [[United States national rugby sevens team]], and is known for his excellent drop kick.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ur7s.com/news/blogumnist/dallen-stanford |title=Ultimate Rugby Sevens, Dallen's USA Eagles Preview, Nov. 29, 2010, |access-date=2012-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026092948/http://ur7s.com/news/blogumnist/dallen-stanford |archive-date=2012-10-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Malifa led the U.S. in scoring during the 2009-10 [[IRB Sevens World Series]] with 120 points, helping the U.S. to its best ever 10th-place finish.<ref>[[United States national rugby sevens team]]</ref> Since 2011, Malifa has been the leading active player for the United States in goals kicked (100+).<ref>[[United States national rugby sevens team]]</ref>\n\n==Family==\nPlaying rugby is all in the family for Nese - his father and three brothers also play the game. Valenese used to play premier Auckland club rugby for the Eden Eagles. It is considered that his twin brother [[Ata Malifa]], was the better player at youth level.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} Their older brother Angelo, was the best fullback in the Eden club.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scrum.com/scrum/rugby/player/15532.html Player Profile]\n*http://web.usarugby.org/cgi-bin/viadesto/natteams/mnt/15ProfileDetail.pl?playerId=367\n\n{{United States Squad 2011 Rugby World Cup}}\n{{United States Squad 2007 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malifa, Nese}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rugby union scrum-halves]]\n[[Category:American rugby union players]]\n[[Category:American Samoan rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Male rugby sevens players]]\n[[Category:United States international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:United States international rugby sevens players]]\n[[Category:Glendale Raptors players]]\n[[Category:Rugby ATL players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n| image = Valenese Malifa Churchill Cup 2010 vs Russia.jpg\n| birth_name = Valenese Malifa\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|9|10}}\n| birth_place =[[American Samoa]]\n| height = {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|180|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| occupation =\n| school =\n| university = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = [[Ata Malifa]] (twin brother)\n| ru_position = [[Rugby union positions#10. Fly-half|Fly-half]]\n| ru_amateuryears = 2009<br>2010-2015\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Belmont Shore RFC]]<br>[[Glendale Merlins|Glendale Raptors]]\n| ru_clubyears = 2019-present\n| ru_proclubs = [[Rugby ATL]]\n| ru_clubcaps = \n| ru_clubpoints = \n| ru_nationalyears = 2007\u20132011\n| ru_nationalteam = [[United States national rugby union team|United States]]\n| ru_nationalcaps = 24\n| ru_nationalpoints = (63)\n| ru_sevensnationalyears = 2007-\n| ru_sevensnationalteam  = [[United States national rugby sevens team|United States]]\n| ru_sevensnationalcomp  = 17   (307)\n| website = \n}}\n'''Valenese Malifa''' (born 10 September 1985 in [[American Samoa]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[rugby union]] [[Rugby union positions#10. Fly-half|fly-half]]. He was a member of the [[United States national rugby union team]] from 2007 until 2011, and participated with the squad at the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]].<ref>[http://www.scrum.com/scrum/rugby/player/15532.html Player Profile]</ref>\n\n==Youth==\nNese Malifa played rugby since he was 17 years old. He played for Auckland and Samoa Rugby Clubs. During his stint in the Pacific Islands, Malifa was a representative rugby player in Auckland in both the XV\u2019s and Sevens game, as well as playing representative rugby in Samoa. Malifa\u2019s talents were noticed by selectors while playing for Ponsonby and then the Eden Club in Auckland. Lesser known are Malifa\u2019s talents in other sporting codes, as Malifa represented Samoa in Cricket.\n\n==Career==\nMalifa played club rugby since moving to the U.S. mainland in 2006, first with [[Belmont Shore]], who Malifa helped reach the 2006 national championship.<ref> Glendale Raptors, [http://www.glendalerugby.com/schedule/2011-2012-season/item/1956-nese-malifa\u2019s-rugby-fairy-tale Nese Malifa's rugby fairy tale], Dec. 5, 2011</ref> Malifa moved to Denver in 2010, where he has been playing with the Glendale Raptors.<ref>Glendale Raptors, [http://www.glendalerugby.com/schedule/2011-2012-season/item/1956-nese-malifa\u2019s-rugby-fairy-tale Nese Malifa's rugby fairy tale], Dec. 5, 2011</ref>\n\nMalifa played flyhalf for the USA Hawks match against Canada West in the 2007 [[North America 4]], notching all of his teams points through two converted tries and two penalty goals from two attempts.\n\nMalifa played flyhalf for the [[United States national rugby union team|United States national team]] since his debut against the England Saxons in 2007.  Malifa made two appearances at the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]] in France, and played 3 matches for the U.S. at the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] in New Zealand. Malifa's highest scoring match to date was against Russia in the [[2011 Churchill Cup]], where Malifa kicked 2 penalties and 3 conversions to lead the team in scoring with 12 points, as the U.S. edged out Russia 32-25.<ref>ESPN Scrum, [http://www.espnscrum.com/churchill-cup-2011/rugby/story/141817.html USA beat Russia for Bowl title], June 18, 2011</ref> As of December 2011, Malifa has tallied 24 caps and 63 points for the U.S. national team.<ref>USA Rugby, [http://web.usarugby.org/cgi-bin/viadesto/natteams/mnt/15ProfileDetail.pl?playerId=367 Men's National Team, Player Profile]</ref>\n\nMalifa plays flyhalf for the [[United States national rugby sevens team]], and is known for his excellent drop kick.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ur7s.com/news/blogumnist/dallen-stanford |title=Ultimate Rugby Sevens, Dallen's USA Eagles Preview, Nov. 29, 2010, |access-date=2012-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026092948/http://ur7s.com/news/blogumnist/dallen-stanford |archive-date=2012-10-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Malifa led the U.S. in scoring during the 2009-10 [[IRB Sevens World Series]] with 120 points, helping the U.S. to its best ever 10th-place finish.<ref>[[United States national rugby sevens team]]</ref> Since 2011, Malifa has been the leading active player for the United States in goals kicked (100+).<ref>[[United States national rugby sevens team]]</ref>\n\n==Family==\nPlaying rugby is all in the family for Nese - his father and three brothers also play the game. Valenese used to play premier Auckland club rugby for the Eden Eagles. It is considered that his twin brother [[Ata Malifa]], was the better player at youth level.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} Their older brother Angelo, was the best fullback in the Eden club.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scrum.com/scrum/rugby/player/15532.html Player Profile]\n*http://web.usarugby.org/cgi-bin/viadesto/natteams/mnt/15ProfileDetail.pl?playerId=367\n\n{{United States Squad 2011 Rugby World Cup}}\n{{United States Squad 2007 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malifa, Nese}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rugby union scrum-halves]]\n[[Category:American rugby union players]]\n[[Category:American Samoan rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Male rugby sevens players]]\n[[Category:United States international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:United States international rugby sevens players]]\n[[Category:Glendale Raptors players]]\n[[Category:Rugby ATL players]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Typo/generalfixes, replaced: teams points \u2192 team's points", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nese_Malifa"}
{"title_page": "Immigration consultant", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Self-published|date=April 2013}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=April 2013}}}}\n\nAn '''immigration consultant''' is a person who helps people to [[Emigration|emigrate]] from one country to another country and through legal and documentation process to increase the chances of immigration for study, work, travel or business purpose. \n\nImmigration consultants may or may not have legal expertise about immigration laws and visa laws and about procedures for obtaining different types of [[Travel visa|visas]], as the designation is regulated by some, but not all, governments. In the United States, immigration consultants/[[notaries]] are not required to have formal immigration law training and are not allowed to answer even the most basic immigration legal questions. Doing so would constitute [[unauthorized practice of law]], which is a crime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oag.ca.gov/consumers/general/immigration_consultants |title=Immigration Consultants &#124; State of California - Department of Justice - Office of the Attorney General |website=Oag.ca.gov |date= |accessdate=2017-06-24}}</ref> Because of this, many organizations including the [[Central America Resource Center]] recommend that all persons seeking immigration assistance completely avoid notaries and immigration consultants and, instead, seek legal advice from a licensed attorney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carecen-la.org/why_should_i_pay_a_notary_or_an_immigration_consultant_if_the_law_permits_him_her_to_do_practically_nothing_for_me |title=Why should I pay a notary or an immigration consultant if the law permits him/her to do practically nothing for me? - Central American Resource Center (CARECEN) |website=Carecen-la.org |date= |accessdate=2017-06-24}}</ref> On the other hand, Canada provides certification as a Regulated Canadian Immigration Consultant through the [[Immigration Consultants of Canada Regulatory Council]], and Australia provides it through the [[Migration Agents Registration Authority]].\n\nImmigration consultants started working in the 1960s{{cn|date=December 2019}} when a large number of qualified people have started migrating from Asia and Latin America to the United States, Canada and Europe. Generally these developed countries have requirement of highly skilled professionals and so they have very strict and complicated rules for immigration and visa processing. To help aid people who need clarity regarding the visa and immigration rules of various countries, this concept of immigration consultancies has come forward.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://iccrc-crcic.ca/ Immigration Consultants of Canada Regulatory Council] (ICCRC)\n* [https://www.mara.gov.au/ Migration Agents Registration Authority]\n* [http://abroadplacements.com/contact.html] (www.abroadplacements.com)\n\n[[Category:Immigration]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Self-published|date=April 2013}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=April 2013}}}}\n\nAn '''immigration consultant''' is a person who helps people to [[Emigration|emigrate]] from one country to another country and through legal and documentation process to increase the chances of immigration for study, work, travel or business purpose. \n\nImmigration consultants may or may not have legal expertise about immigration laws and visa laws and about procedures for obtaining different types of [[Travel visa|visas]], as the designation is regulated by some, but not all, governments. In the United States, immigration consultants/[[notaries]] are not required to have formal immigration law training and are not allowed to answer even the most basic immigration legal questions. Doing so would constitute [[unauthorized practice of law]], which is a crime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oag.ca.gov/consumers/general/immigration_consultants |title=Immigration Consultants &#124; State of California - Department of Justice - Office of the Attorney General |website=Oag.ca.gov |date= |accessdate=2017-06-24}}</ref> Because of this, many organizations including the [[Central America Resource Center]] recommend that all persons seeking immigration assistance completely avoid notaries and immigration consultants and, instead, seek legal advice from a licensed attorney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carecen-la.org/why_should_i_pay_a_notary_or_an_immigration_consultant_if_the_law_permits_him_her_to_do_practically_nothing_for_me |title=Why should I pay a notary or an immigration consultant if the law permits him/her to do practically nothing for me? - Central American Resource Center (CARECEN) |website=Carecen-la.org |date= |accessdate=2017-06-24}}</ref> On the other hand, Canada provides certification as a Regulated Canadian Immigration Consultant through the [[Immigration Consultants of Canada Regulatory Council]], and Australia provides it through the [[Migration Agents Registration Authority]].\n\nImmigration consultants started working in the 1960s{{cn|date=December 2019}} when a large number of qualified people have started migrating from Asia and Latin America to the United States, Canada and Europe. Generally these developed countries have requirement of highly skilled professionals and so they have very strict and complicated rules for immigration and visa processing. To help aid people who need clarity regarding the visa and immigration rules of various countries, this concept of immigration consultancies has come forward.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://iccrc-crcic.ca/ Immigration Consultants of Canada Regulatory Council] (ICCRC)\n* [https://www.mara.gov.au/ Migration Agents Registration Authority]\n\n[[Category:Immigration]]\n", "name_user": "Mkarthikkittu", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immigration_consultant"}
